WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:05.120
Okay, so we have a brand new slash command added&nbsp;
to Claude Code, which is likely preparing us for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:11.920
when Claude Myphos releases. So it's /advisor.&nbsp;
So when you do /advisor, you can configure the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:16.560
advisor tool and it should take you to something&nbsp;
like this. And essentially this is a tool that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:20.800
built into Claude Code for when it requires&nbsp;
stronger judgment about a particular problem.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:26.160
Now you can see right now we only have Sonnet and&nbsp;
Opus. So if you're on Opus, ideally you want your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:31.200
main model in Claude Code to be on Sonnet. So you&nbsp;
do /model and then pick Sonnet. And essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.960
when you're coding with the Sonnet model and&nbsp;
it ends up getting stuck, then it would call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.960 --> 00:00:43.280
the advisor tool to ask Opus a question. This is&nbsp;
kind of similar to /model opusplan whereby Sonnet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:49.040
is used all the time except for when you're in&nbsp;
planning mode, in which case Opus is used. So if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:53.040
you were to combine the two together, you would&nbsp;
have a really good plan at the very beginning,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:57.600
then it would switch over to Sonnet for the actual&nbsp;
execution. And if Sonnet ends up getting stuck&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:01.920
with something, then it would call the advisor&nbsp;
tool to ask Opus what the deal is here. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:07.920
right now with /advisor, you can only see that&nbsp;
we have Opus 4.6 and Sonnet 4.6. So if you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:12.480
already on Opus and you're using Opus as advisor,&nbsp;
you'd probably not see much benefit to doing that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:17.680
over using a subagent of sorts. And if you're&nbsp;
in Haiku, then you may want to use Sonnet 4.6.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:23.120
Now what they will likely be adding here in the&nbsp;
future is like Myphos for their upcoming model,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:27.840
because chances are since it's so expensive, we&nbsp;
won't be able to afford it most of the time. Until&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:31.760
like prices come down and stuff in the future.&nbsp;
So I imagine what many people will be doing in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:38.000
Claude Code is sticking to Opus and then having&nbsp;
the advisor call Myphos with the entire like chat&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.560
history and log to help it work around like a&nbsp;
particularly hard problem. Now the way that it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:47.360
works behind the scenes is that essentially the&nbsp;
tool description consults a stronger reviewer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:52.480
who sees your full conversation transcript. There&nbsp;
are no parameters. When you call advisor(), your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:57.680
entire history — task, every tool call and result,&nbsp;
your reasoning — is automatically forwarded. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:02.480
advisor sees exactly what you've done. Now, of&nbsp;
course, you can tell Claude Code to call this tool&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:08.640
when you're stuck, but it says it will be called&nbsp;
before any substantive work. So before writing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:12.880
before committing to an interpretation, before&nbsp;
building an assumption. And it's also called when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:19.040
the model believes the task is complete. So it's&nbsp;
told to first make deliverable durable first and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:23.040
then actually call the advisor. When stuck,&nbsp;
errors recurring, approaches not converging,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:28.480
results don't fit, or when considering a change&nbsp;
of approach. Now guidance on frequency says,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:32.640
on tasks longer than a few steps, call it at&nbsp;
least once before committing to an approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:37.520
and once declaring done. On short reactive tasks,&nbsp;
skip it. Which means that if you ask Claude Code&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:41.440
to change some colors around, then it will not&nbsp;
call the advisor because it's too simple of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:46.000
task. Now this is a part that's interesting. So&nbsp;
how to weigh the advice. Give it serious weight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.560
as you would expect. And if the empirical results&nbsp;
contradict advisor advice, surface the conflict&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:56.880
with another advisor call rather than silently&nbsp;
switching. So I find this part particularly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.880 --> 00:03:00.800
interesting. I'd like to see that in action.&nbsp;
And now it's like a passing self-test is not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:05.120
evidence that the advice is wrong. Now this is a&nbsp;
summary of the tool description. If you want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:09.520
read the full one, then it will be down below in&nbsp;
the pinned comment. Now let's see this in action.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:14.400
If I go to previous session and this is some bug&nbsp;
that Claude Code found with the billing logic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:18.640
if I wanted to call the advisor, I could either&nbsp;
like tell it directly or Claude Code during the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:23.360
execution may realize that it needs to call&nbsp;
the advisor. So we already have it set over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:28.000
here with Opus. And I will just say, hey, can&nbsp;
you call the advisor to check that this will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.480
be the solution here? And then pressing enter, it&nbsp;
now says advising using Opus 4.6. And the advisor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:39.120
basically flagged two things over here that&nbsp;
we would want our Sonnet model to consider.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:42.560
Now it seems that there are some things&nbsp;
to bear in mind when doing this. Firstly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:46.800
it seems that the advisor like can't actually&nbsp;
consult extra files on your machine. The entire&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:51.280
chat history is being passed to the advisor. And&nbsp;
then that result is being passed back into your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:55.600
session. So as they showed on Twitter, this is&nbsp;
what it looks like. You have the main executor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.600 --> 00:04:00.240
being Sonnet. You have the shared context that&nbsp;
has been accumulated so far in the history,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:05.280
which is a conversation, tools, and so forth. And&nbsp;
then the executor can call the advisor on demand.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:09.200
That advisor would send feedback and that would&nbsp;
be added to shared context, which likely means&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:13.280
that any future advisor can see any previous&nbsp;
advice that previous advisors have given. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:17.600
when it comes to benchmarking, they found that&nbsp;
using this approach is slightly cheaper if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:22.400
were paying for raw API tokens, but it would mean&nbsp;
that it consumes less usage limits on your Claude&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:27.040
Code plan as well. And you also do get slightly&nbsp;
better performance on some of these benchmarks.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:31.600
Now I will personally not be using this that much&nbsp;
because I use Opus all the time and I don't see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:38.000
any benefit in getting another Opus advisor with&nbsp;
the same chat history so far to give advice. I'd&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.800
rather get advice from a subagent that has an&nbsp;
independent context. But I would see myself&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:47.760
using this in the future whereby if Myphos is&nbsp;
released, basically swapping this all around,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:52.480
I would have the main executor being Opus because&nbsp;
it's still a very capable model. And then getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:56.800
advice from Myphos instead. And this is probably&nbsp;
one of the ways they're planning on making Myphos&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.800 --> 00:05:01.360
accessible to us once it is released, because&nbsp;
apparently it will be really expensive. Now, if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:04.800
you do like this kind of stuff, then do subscribe&nbsp;
to the channel because I do make the most&nbsp;&nbsp;

